\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is real-symmetric and invertible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is real-symmetric too.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In 18.06, you were shown a simple (2--3 line) proof that the eigenvalues
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{x}=\lambda\vec{x}$
\end_inset

) must be real numbers if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is real-symmetric (if you've forgot it, look it up), eigenvectors of distinct
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be orthogonal.
 Now consider the eigenproblem 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{-1}A\vec{x}=\lambda\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are both real-symmetric and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite.
 In this class, we denote 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dot products
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{x},\vec{y}\rangle$
\end_inset

, where the familiar dot product of column vectors is 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{x},\vec{y}\rangle=\vec{x}^{*}\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 (recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 denotes conjugate-transpose) .
 Consider a modified 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dot product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\vec{x},\vec{y}\rangle_{B}=\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Using this new dot product, adapt your 18.06 proof to show that the eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{-1}A$
\end_inset

 are also real, and its eigenvectors of distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal under this new dot product.
\end_layout

